<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-01-09T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-01-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="1721" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1721">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 419.11D29/48.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to Minister <persName type="to">Price</persName>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 16.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-01-09">
                                    <hi rend="italic">January 9, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department has received your No. 51
                            of the 23d ultimo<note n="4" xml:id="d1721fn4">
                                <ref target="frus1913#pg_1080">Id. 1080</ref>.</note> in which you
                            report that you transmitted in person to Señor Lefevre a note vigorously
                            insisting upon a prompt closing of the negotiations in regard to demands
                            made by the Government of the United States growing out of the assault
                            on American sailors and marines in the Cocoa Grove district, July 4,
                            1912.</p>
                        <p>Your action is approved. The Department hopes to receive at an early date
                            information of the acquiescence by the Panaman Government in the just
                            and reasonable demands which the United States has made in this
                            matter.</p>
                        <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">J. B. Moore</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>